{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_dollyvarden_ver01/data/sn85042379/00295861149/1920122401/0437.xml":{"full_text":"The Glasgow\nCourier^\nPublished Every Frida p at\nGLASGOW, jsTONTANA\nfacceeding the Valley County Independent\nT. J. HOCKING, Editor\nOfficial\nOfficial\nI ity\nCounty\nPaper\nPaper\nEntered at the Postoffice at Glasgow. Montana,\nu second class matter October 6th, 1911\nTELEPHONE 4*\nAdvertising rates for weekly, monthly and\nyearly contract* furnished upon application.\nA RESOLUTION\nTO be patriots, rather than\npartisans; to win the peace\nby reviving the idealism which\nwon the war; to broaden our\noutlook and narrow our ani\nmosities; to carry into national\nand international affairs the\nmaxims which guide gentlemen\nand gentlewomen in their daily\nconduct; to practice thrift that\nwe may be able to practice\ncharity; to recognize that each\nof us is and always must be\nhis brother's keeper; to work\nwell that there may be plenty of\ngoods in the world and think\nwell that they may be rightly\ndistributed; to go forward each\nday to a higher level of purpose\nand effectiveness, and live as\none afraid of no man. and of\nwhom no just man is afraid.\n\u2014Selected.\nTHE COMING OF OUR LADY, 1921\nThe threshold of a New Year ap\nproaches. The cartoonists like to\npicture and represent 1921 as an in\nfant, but it would seem most appro\npriate to forecast it as a woman\u2014not\nnecessarily \"beautiful\" woman\u2014for all\nwomen are beautiful.\nIt would be most appropriate to\nhave 1921 typify Womanhood for good\nand sufficient reasons. One is that the\ncoming year would have no interest\nwhatever in war. or the things of war.\nThis old world has had sufficient of\nturmoil and strife during the past de\ncade; and if women hail their way\nthere would not be another inter\nnational disturbance.\nIf 1921 typified the spirit of woman- 1\nhood, the world would see more of\nreal sound religion and more of the\ngood things that come out of it. The\nsynics, the Bolshevists and the ex\nploiters of mankind in general may\nsneer at religion, but God in the form\nthat we civilized people have come to\nknow Him, has been a comfort and a\nhigh inspiration to untold billions of\npeople in the past; and He would be\nagain an inspiration to untold billions\nin the future if only these untold bil\nlions of people would so allow Him.\nThe earth needs a great revival of\nreligion in 1921.\nNo, not the infant, 1921; but the\nWoman, 1921; for if our New Year is\najiything like Women we will see more\nco-operation in the real things of life,\nand much more gentleness and human\nE3 ft\n13\n\n009\nB\nTM II, l\nF oresighted Economy in\nArt Metal\nIt is the cost per year of service that indicates how much you pay\nfor filing cabinets, just as cost per mile determines what you pay\nfor tires.\nConsidered on this basis Art Metal steel office equipment is the\nlowest priced equipment you can buy.\nThere is no wear out to it. It serves efficiently year after year,\nprotecting your records from fire, water and dirt; and its good\nlooks are a constant source of pride and satisfaction to you.\nSee this better office furniture at our store.\nThe Glasgow Courier\nsympathy and love in 1921. The\nmonster \"Hate\" has encircled the\nworld and inflicted its wounds on\ncountless hearts. Only human sym\npathy, kindness and love will heal the\ndeadly hurts that the human race lias\nsuffered.\nLEMUEL GIBSON\nIt is fitting indeed that the citizens\nof Valley county should pause and\nbear testimony to the esteem mi which\nthey held Lemuel Gibson and to the\napprobation which he so well deserved\nas a constructive pioneer and philan\nthropist. Their utterances may not\ntestify to the real lustre of his name,\nbut they will brighten and strengthen\nthe links of the \"chain which should\nbind the citizens of the North country\nin public or private business affairs\ntogether.\" Those who encountered him\nwill never forget his ability and his\nenergy and his honesty. His name\nwill go down to posterity in eastern\nfinance, or captain of industry or\nMontana, not as that of a master o\u00ef\nwizard of invention, or prodigy ot\"\nstatecraft, but as that of one of the\nfathers of this great and spacious and\nwonderful commonwealth, Montana.\nLemuel Gibson's whole life was a\ncampaign of pluck, perserverenee. and\nprinciple. He lexoelled not in the\neasy excellence of things said, but in\nthe arduous excellence of things done.\nTo extoll his spirit of enterprise, his j\nrespect for the rights of others, the\ninnate sense of justice, and of reason,\nwhich kept him steadfast to his pur- j\nposes, his cheerful, genial presence,\nthe blamelessness of his life, could lie j\nnecessary only among those who did I\nnot know him. His span of life was j\nmore than three score, and up to the\nlast his spirit never faltered or\nflagged. No labor discouraged him,\nno contingency appalled him. no dis\nadvantage or defeat dismayed him.\nDay by day ha continued on the jour\nney of life, meeting actual affairs and\nrealities and grappling with them with\na grasp resolute and quick.\nNobly and well did Lemuel Gibson\nlive; full of years and honor for worthy\naccomplishment he died. His achieve\nment as a pioneer is one that the\nstate of Montana, and especially the\nNorth Country will ever hold in grate\nful honoring memory. It is not neces\nsary here to repeat the story of a ca\nreer which every citizen of Valley\ncoun+v and northeastern Montana\nshould know. His life was devoted\nnot alone to the service of the citv and\nthe county that he helped to build, but\nto the welfare of the whole of the\npeople; his memory is enduringly as\nsociated with events which have had\nto do with the pioneer work of the\ngreat Northwest.\nIndeed the people of northeastern\nMontana owe much to the life and\nworks of Lemuel Gibson.\nWORLD'S GREATEST PRODUCER\nThe United States is the most pro\nductive country on earth. It leads all\nthe rest of the globe in yields of the\nmine, the soil, and the factory. This\nfact was tersely and cogently set forth\nby Judge Elbert H. Gray, chairman\nof the Board of the United States\nSteel Corporation, in an address which\nhe made before the American Iron\nand Steel Institute, Judge Gary said:\n\"Notwithstanding the United States\nhas only 6 per cent of the world's pop\nulation, and but 7 per cent of the\nworld's land, we produce:\n\"20 per cent of the world's supply of\ngold.\n\"25 per cent of the world's supply\nof wheat.\n\"40 per cent of the world's supply\nof iron and steel.\n\"40 per cent of the world's supply\nof lead.\n\"40 per cent of the world's supply\nof silver.\n\"50 per cent of the world's supply\nof zinc.\n\"52 per cent of the world's supply\nof coal.\n\"60 per cent of the world's supply\nof aluminum.\n\"(>0 per cent of the world's supply of\ncopper.\n\"tiO per cent of the world's supply of\ncotton.\n\"6(5 per cent of the world's supply of\nof\n\"75 per cent of the world's supply\nof corn.\n\"65 per cent of the world's supply\nof automobiles.\"\nIn face of a marvelous showing like\nthat, who can for a moment doubt\nthe future prosperity of this country?\nWHAT THE AMERICAN\nFARMER WANTS\nThere is support here and support\nthere for various other planks\u2014planks\nradical; and planks conservative; but\nfrom a careful analysis of the situa\ntion, it would appear, that the fol\nlowing as advocated by one reliable\nstudent of the situation comes nearest\nto what the majority of the farmers\nat this time want from Congress:\nAmendment or interpretation of the\nanti-trust laws which will make it\nlegal for the farmer to engage in col\nlective marketing.\nStrengthening of the Federal Farm\nLoan System.\nInterstate Commerce legislation\nmaking compulsory the honest adver\ntising and labeling of woolen fabrics,\nfood and drugs.\nDevelopment of inland waterways\nwith ocean outlets.\nIS(nac/nen< of cooperative credit\nplans to provide funds for farmers.\nNational control of packers.\nImmigration laws which will main\ntain American standards of citizenship.\nOperation of air nitrate plant by\ngovernment or lease for purpose of\nproviding cheap fertilizer.\nThe appropriation of funds to per\nmit Department of Agriculture to\nmake studies of cost of production of\nfarm products.\nDisapproval of any system which\ndenies to the individual the right to\nwork in any place where his industry\nis needed and at any wage which is\nsatisfactory to him.\nAccording to the newspapers pub\nlished in the two towns, Culbertson\nand Bainville editors seem to have for\ngotten that the election has long since\ncome and gone. Some kind friend\nshould donate each of these editors a\nsack of marbles and let them fight it\nout \"fer keeps\" in the alley.\nTownley states that he will leave\nNorth Dakota, having \"completed\"\nhis work in that state. He adds that lie\nwill enter a new field of work for the\nLeague. It is not at all probable, on\nthe strength of the recent Montana\nelection returns that he will choose\nthis as a congenial field.\nThe Dubuque Times-Journal states:\n\"Fellow Citizens, on March the fourth\nnext, the people of the United States\nwill inaugurate, not anoint, a presi\ndent.\"\nMembers of the new \"league of no\ntions,\" are beginning now to feel that\nthey would rather retain at least just\na little of their self determination.\nBUNK\nBp .he Cub Reporter\nLIAS G AI' ON \"PLAY\nING THE GAME*'\n\"It mus. V ius-t s >me life down m\nWashington these days,\" remarked\nLias Gap, as he perched ins number\nten's upon the corner of my cies.< last\nSaturday, and applied the tire to his\nage-old, aromatic corn cob pipe.\n\"In what respect?\" we queried of\nthe friendly old visitor.\n\"Well, sir. Cub,\" replied Lias, \"with\nthe League of Nations and the Peace\nTreaty one minute, the farm relief\nquestion the next; and then war bu\nreau investigation committes' reports,\nthe tariff, immigration, and a score of\nother things all piling one upon the\nother, it surely cannot be a midsum\nmer's vacation period for some of our\nlegislators, at least.\n\"I am not much given to political\ndiscussion, but I like to refer to politics\nonce in a while for a\u2014well, just a\nsort of diversion from the regular\nmonotonies of life.\n\"You know. Cub, politics sure have\nchanged a lot the past few years. The\nman of years ago, who has not been\nworking at the game steady, wouldn't\nhave a ghost of a show in this political\nera.\n\"I belonged to a time when there\nwere two parties, and those two par\nties were practically inclusive of the\nsame personages. I expect that you\nremember when the mugwump first\ncame into disrepute. But now, they\nhave come into repute. The man who\nlooked both ways didn't exist then. That\nmade it perfectly safe going. You were\neither this or that, but now you ara\nneither this nor that. And, that\nevolves a whole lot of food for the\nhumorous mind. Take for instance\nwhen the late Mr. Roosevelt went to\nNew York City and Syracuse in the\nmemorable Progressive Crusade; he\nwent into the state campaign and\nnominated New York State officers;\nthey sang \"Onward Christian Sol\ndiers.\" and nominated a Jew fur\nI\nI\nI\ngovernor.\n\"Well, it is just such\nlightful infelicities which occur ail\nalong the line, that render it impos\nsible for a man to know just what to\ni do. Take for instance our President.\nI didn't vote for Mr. Wilson, but I\nI have approved of a few things that\nhe has done, but always with the same\nI sort of travelling smile on my face,\nbecause it has sure been funnier than\na goat; the whole situation. If I were\ngoing to draw a picture of politics\nas they have existed the past two\nyears, I know just exactly what I\nwould do. I suppose that you, some\nI few months ago, noticed in some of\nI the dailies of the state, a picture puz\nzle in the form of a cartoon, where\nthe artist drew a Red Cross nurse with\na lot of scenery, flourishes etc; arid\nsays 'Find the other Red Cross nurse;'\nand you turn the thing up side down\nand down side up two or three times,\nand wonder and look for the mys\nterious nurse. Well, I'd take for my\nj chart about five figures; one would\nj be 'watchful waiting,' and one 'too\ni proud to fight,' and one 'lie kept us\nout of war,' and one 'peace without\nvictory', and one 'freedom of th\nseething de- I\nseas.' Then I would put underneath j\nit, 'Find Wilson.' Of course that's not\nDure criticism\u2014that's just the fun of\ni it. Just goes to show the trend of\nthe times in wiji.ch we are living;\nwhere one never- knows where they\nare going to landHhe next day.\n\"And speaking about farm legisla\ntion, and the high cost of living;\nthere is just another proof of the great\nsurprising world We live in today. I\nwas talking to a friend of mine the\nother day who lives in one of the big\nwheat belts of the west, and he told\nme that in his neighborhood, they\nhave multiplied and improved the farm\nmachinery so that it has become nec\nessary to build gymnasiums on the\nfarms to give the farm hands exercise.\nThat raises the cost of a bushel of\nwheat, a barrel of flour, a loaf of\nbread, and there you are.\n\"A friend of mine is trying to cross\nthe strawberry plant and milkweed\nso that he can have strawberries and\ncream without keeping a cow. I asked\nhim once how about the expenses of it?\nlie replied: 'Damn the expenses; we\nhave lots \u00ab.f them.'\n\"They say that since the war these\nexploiting opportunities have brought\nso many millionaires, common ordin\nary people who don't know table\nmanners but have the money, that\nMr. Burbank is trying to make square\npeas so that the millionaire can eat\nthem with a knife without them rolling\noff.\n\"And, it's just the same with th<>\nfamer as it is with the politician and\nall the rest of us. It is all because of\nthe great world we are living in. And,\nwe can't change things. We have\ngot to take the world as it comes to\nus. We can't have everything to\nplease us. You know some people\nwant to stabilize things, and have\nthem even. A fellow said the other\nday that if he was born again, he would\nwant to be born half Irish and half\nJew, for the Irishman always needed\nfifty cents and the Jew always had it.\nThis fellow wanted to play safe. But\nthere is no life, no vitality and no\ncourage in playing safe. Nothing ven\ntured, nothing gained.\n\"And, no legislation is going\nbring about the speedy readjustment\nto\nf the affairs of this 'great' world in j\nwhich we live. VYe must all play the\ngame and have faith.\n\".Surely politics have changed an.l\nso has almost everything else. Of\ncourte, it does not seem just right\nj\n.--\u00abw\n\u00abto\ns\nVILLI AM S HART\nin 'THE TOLL GATE'\nA PARAMOUNT ARTCRAFT PICTURE\nOrpheum \u2014Sunday Monday\nDec. 26. 27.\u2014Prices\u2014 20c -40c 50c\nand proper to most of us, but why\nget discouraged at a time which calls\nfor courage and grit\n\"You know sometimes, I creep off\nin among the books I used to pore\nin my acedemic life, philosophy,\ntheology, poetry and literature, and I\nsay to myself, 'the world has all gone\nwrong, this is the real stuff.' And,\nthen I hear my little girl singing\n'Johnny get you gun', and I say, T\nbelieve she acts like she is alive, too,'\nThen, I say to myself, 'It seems kind\nof strange; it don't seem quite what\nI was brought up to, but here goes.\nI want to be in the game.'\n\"We are living in a new century.\nDiscouragement and aloofness will\nnot help. They should be barred. You\nknow I once got discouraged, and was\nfeeling down on the whole world, and\nI ran onto an old friend of mine who\nshoved his big fist up into my face\nsaid: 'Lias, the Lord reigns, and the\ndevil hasn't got all the umberellas.'\n\"So, you see, Cub, perhaps- it isn't\nthe queemess of politics and these\nother things, it is the new century that\nwe are living in; and if you and\nI are to get our share of the benefits,\nwe will just simply have to stiffen up\nthe vertibrae and play the game with\nthe rest of them.\"\nff\u00eee\nTrend of the State\nPress\nThe PASSING OF TOWNLEY\nThe moral to be drawn from the\nbirth of Xownleyism, the brief but\ngorgeous career of the Nonpartisans,\nand the passing of Townley, is that the\nsafety of American institutions rests\nsecure in the intelligence of the peo\nple, which up to this date has risen\nsuperior to every dangerous occasion.\n\u2014The Belgrade Journal.\nTHINGS MIGHT BE A LOT WORSE\nSince the splendid beating the rad\nicals got in this state and nation at\nthe election they are more convinced\nthan ever that the country is ruined,\nThey should go to the Old Man Ex\nperience and get something for their\npessimism. This ain't such a bad\ncountry\u2014now that the election went\nthe way it did.\u2014Helena Record Her\nald.\nWOMEN IN POLITICS\nHowever, the fact that women can\ndidates have been elected occasionally\nshows that it can be done, even with\nout the concerted aid of their sex, and\nwoman office-holders probably will\nbecome more numerous as time goes\non.\nStill, the indications are that those\nwho prophesied a sex war after suf\nfrage were badly mistaken. The\nMissoulian.\nTHE WAVE OF CRIME\nWe hope the experts will diagnose\nthe cause of the present epidemic of\ncrime and convince the public that\nthey have found the true cause of\nthe social disease from which we are\nsuffering. If we were sure of that\nthen we might more quickly find the\nremedy and apply it. At present\nwe have too many conflicting ex\nof the trouble\nFalls Tribune.\nand its cure.\u2014Great\nopinions^ both about the cause\n\nTIME TO CLEAN HOUSE\nIt is time to clean house at the Uni\nversity of Montana. The people of\nthis state are not paying university\nprocessors to sell ^stock in radical\nnewspapers or organize publications\nfor the spreading of Bolshevist doc\ntrine.\nMontana had a close escape in No\nvember. We ought to be thankful for\nit and appreciate the fact that we did\nescape, let's clean house and begin\nwith the university professors who are\ndevoting their energies to promoting\nradical newspapers and spreading the\npoison of red card socialism.\u2014Helena\nIndependent.\nSTABILIZING BUSINESS\nThere was some danger, to he sure,\nin the sudden and abrupt drop in\nprices, which hanpily has been checked.\nIt might have threatened to have be\ncome disrupting. Business conditions\nhave not been basicly unsound, except\npossibly in the inflation of prices and\ncredits, and what was needed was a\ngradual descent to ensure a safe re\nturn to normalcy.\nIn the light of such a brief review\nit is the confident opinion as expressed,\nthat business conditions are stabilized\nto a large extent and what is needed is\na restoration of faith of the future\nwith an optimistic spirit, with busi\nness conditions and public support\nholding up each others' hands.\u2014Miles\nCity Star.\nMINDING OUR OWN BUSINESS\nThe American ship of state is drift\ning into dangerous waters. The Ja\npanese question is assuming a serious\naspect. A spark may easily start a\nwar. and we do not think the Ameri\ncan people are crazy about another\nwar. if it may be honorably avoided.\nSo long as the United States remains\noutside the League of Nations we\nmay not hope for aid or sympathy\nfrom the nations within the league.\nOur first duty is to join the league.\nbut since we have been prevented from\ndoing that by a group of log-roling\nj politicians, it would appear the part\nof wisdom as well as safety for us to\n\nj an\nj attend very closely to our own busi\nness, rather than to go about looking\nfor trouble by mixing in the house\nof other nations.\u2014The Missoul\nRESOLUTION OF CONDOLENCE\nWhereas, it has pleased Almighty\nGod to call from our midst Lemuel W.\nGibson, who was a loyal member of\nour organization:\nNow, therefore, be it Resolved, th.it\nby bis death our organization, the City\nof Glasgow, the County of Valley, and\nthe State of Montana, have suffered\na great loss; for Mr. Gibson was a re\nmarkable character, whose life was\nmost worthy.\nHe was a pioneer of the West; he\ncame to the trackless prairies in 1884,\nas a hunter of buffaloes; he fought\nagainst the hostile Indians; he braved\nSKEKEKSSfSUSSKSKSKSKSS\nToilet\n\"KEJCSM\nM\nS\nH\nS\nH\nPreparations\nHall Drug Co.\nTo YOU and YOUR\nNEW YEAR\nMay your New Year's Day\ncontain the same amount of Hap\npiness as your Christmas Day,\nand may each Today in the New\nYear prove Happier and Bright\ner than its Yesterday\u2014and each\nTomorrow Brighter and Happier\nthan its Today.\n\u2014Bregenzer.\nIX\n1J1G\nmpvUum\nthe perils of a strange land; wedded\nto the free, open life of the rolling\nplains, he engaged in the cattle and\nsheep business, in which, by virtue of\nhis wonderful energy and wise judg\nment, he greatly prospered.\nHe loved the dumb animals, and he\nloved mankind, and, like the Lowly\nNazarene, he was a loved and loving\nShepherd.\nThe storms were never too fierce\nto drive him from the care of his\nflocks; and no human appeal for aid\nwas ever made to him in vain.\nHis life was as clean and true as\nthe glint and the course of the stars,\nwhich he loved to study while guard\ning his herds during countless nights\nof ceaseless vigil.\nMuch of the progress of Northern\nMontana is due to his unselfish exten\nsion of financial aid to enterprise-;\ntfAm\nma/r\nWsj\nJANUARY SEVENTH\nWill Be Too Late!\nIt's never been done yet. The man who\nputs off until January 7 \"to start the New\nYear right\" by SAVING SO MUCH EACH\nWEEK\u2014and always has had others places for\nhis money when the calendar \"sevens.'\nIf it's only fifty cents\u2014put it in the\nbank New Year eve\u2014Dec. 31\u2014and make a\nresolve to add to it weekly\u2014THEN WATCH\nIT GROW. AT FIVE PER CENT.\nFarmers-Stockgrowers Bank\n\u00c0 Happy New Year\nv\nVt\nH\u00ab\n1921! The dawn of better days\u2014the be\nginning of better times for all people.\nMay the new year bring you sunshine and\nhappiness, a return of prosperity!\nFor the favors accorded us in the stren\nuous year just ended, our grateful thanks\u2014\nfor the year commencing, a practical demon\nstration of our appreciation of your valued\npatronage.\nGlasgow Neat Market\nL. E. WELLS\nlooking toward the development of our\nresources and the bettering of civic\nand religious conditions; while his\npurse was always open for private\nloans to the needy, and for gifts to\nthose in distress.\nIt might well be said of him that\n\"If every one for whom he did a lov\ning favor should bring a blossom to\nhis grave, he would sleep tonight be\nneath a wilderness of flowers.\"\nAnd be it further Resolved that\nthese Resolutions be spread on our\nminutes, and copies forwarded to the\nrelatives of the deceased, and to the\npublic press.\nDated December 22, 1920.\nGLASGOW CHAMBER OF COM\nMERCE AND AGRICULTURE.\nBy its Committee:\nOtto M. Christinson.\nJohn L. Slattery.","height":"21768","width":"16392"}}
